The National Assembly Joint Committee on Ecology and Climate Change has urged contractors handling the projects for the remediation of polluted sites in Ogoniland to expedite action on completing the project. The chairman, Senate Committee on Ecology and Climate Change, Sen. Hassan Mohammed Gusau, made this call when he led the joint committee on an inspection tour of the sites in Ogoniland. The lawmaker, who noted the remediation process requires much technicalities which should not be rushed, however, urged contractors to rise up to the occasion and stop making excuses. He revealed his committee had received many petitions from stakeholders and NGOs about the activities of the Hydrocarbon Pollution Remediation Project (HYPREP) concerning the Ogoni clean up, and having seen for himself, believed the project is on course, although he cannot give an expert opinion as a non professional” he said. Earlier, HYPREP’s project coordinator, Dr. Marvin Dekil, urged the National Assembly to support the project, especially since it was the first time such project was been carried out in Nigeria. Also, the executive director of Environmental Rights Action, Dr. Godwin Ojo, said discussions was ongoing for a legislative backing, that 20 per cent of Ogoni clean-up funds go into empowerment of Ogoni people who were negatively impacted by the pollution.